The menu of a child with a fatty habit: skipping breakfast and eating sausage for dinner
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that children who are obese are more likely to come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
Once again, the environment in which a person grows up and the examples around him are vital to his healthy development.
On the tables of obese children, sausage is up to half as common as in families with normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner the day before the "Obesity is Not an Accident" campaign.
In families with fat children, exercise is not a favorite activity, but it is also the case for the majority of today's students - only 15 percent said that their parents take time to exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out towards the end of the school year last year and involved nearly 900 children from primary schools throughout the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the campaign "Obesity is no accident", which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12 000 pupils from fourth to eighth grades have taken part in the project.
Poor diet and lack of exercise in the family are key factors responsible for the alarming increase in the number of children who are overweight or even obese.
"Only half of the children surveyed said they ate breakfast, lunch, dinner, and dinner five times a day - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet", says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relatively small things, such as a regular family breakfast, are important for a child's healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of school families eat breakfast.
And in most families, everyone eats breakfast for themselves.
Worst of all, one in 10 families don't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey also revealed that families with overweight children are much more likely to consume unhealthy potatoes.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, less than half of their parents do - 15 percent.
Make your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own diet plan from the options offered, according to their appetite and opinion.
"The preference of Czech children between 12 and 15 years old for nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite foods were many flour dishes, meat dishes, and, of course, desserts.
"The high popularity of sweet lemonade is particularly alarming", says the final report on the survey.
For lunch, the main course, the dough barely beat the chicken.
Legumes were almost unpopular among the children, and fish and vegetable dishes were very unpopular at lunch.
A Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if given the right information.
"In the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the instructional lecture 'Obesity is not a coincidence', there was in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy eating", the project results state.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to prefer ordinary water.
The children also reported much more frequent choices of chicken or fish as the main course of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
Professionals say - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article on how stylists learn, I was a bit grumpy that this was a bit too much material to start with.
I had no idea what was coming.
Lectures by three industry professionals, the clothing of problematic figures and a seminar on how to do it "on the square".
I'm afraid it's going to get worse.
The closer we get to the exam, the more information and practical tasks we have to face.
But even though the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it is still full.
This time we debated with the director, Alena (not a single man participates in the course), how to dress a woman who does not have an ideal proportioned figure.
And that's what most of us are.
Some have a neck too short, others a figure too youthful without proper curves, and still others are plump.
It is up to the stylist to visually conceal the broad shoulders, lengthen the neck, or create the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a woman like Jennifer Lopez -- so with big breasts, wide hips and a narrow waist -- in a nice, well-fitting way without being too provocative.
For example, if the waist-hip gap is so large that the skirt or trousers really do not fit, at least one piece should be tailored to your size.
You will not regret it, for good-fitting clothing is priceless.
A custom-made skirt like this is much better than one that's too high and too slippery, too waist-high, and so on.
Younger characters may, in turn, wear clothing with creases, braids, appliqués, embroidery, or racking.
With all this information and character types, I'm glad I have a whole week to think it over.
And yet I'm afraid that it's almost impossible to do, given the homework.
Each of the students was assigned a celebrity to design outfits for - day dress and evening dress.
We should take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the respective star and the type of figure.
I'm supposed to "dress up" Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
I am happy inside, because this is much better for me personally than, for example, to wear Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has recently gained probably a hundred kilos (well, that's a bit exaggerated), or even the young Selena Gomez.
We are told to cut out garments from magazines or search the Internet, print them out, and then graphically edit them.
The resulting "Moodboard", as the whole thing is called, is intended to express our very personal style and our relationship with graphic design.
It's very important to think about the graphic side of styling as well.
The stylist not only attracts the models physically, but also designs the so-called product page in the magazines (according to specific requirements, for example, trend handbags, coats, etc.).
That's what the stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us.
But that's not until Sunday.
That means a stylist has to have a good overview.
The Saturday lecture, which was filled with information on the types of figures, was immediately spiced up by three visitors from the industry:
The project is led by the designer Jan Pokorný, the fashion designer Jakub Polanka and the fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and that a stylist should be able to exploit it.
And a skilled stylist can work in a variety of ways with a single garment.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat as a regular over your jeans, like a T-shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on your naked body, put on heels, and wear it as a dress.
You just have to roll up your sleeves or your collar and the whole look is different.
"Play with it", he insisted.
But the advice that stood out to me was this: "You must first know the rules perfectly".
"Then you may hurt her", said Jacob.
I finally understand why we have to put all these doctrines together, what you can combine with what, and why, even if in fashion magazines you often see something completely different.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist has to prepare many more outfits before he's going to take a photo.
So for a fashion story with ten pages (say ten outfits) you have to be prepared to style at least fifteen.
And also that the clothes in the photo, when combined with other accessories, sometimes look very different than in reality.
So, all of this has to be taken into account when designing the outfit.
Jan Pokorný also confirmed that image and style are sometimes half of success.
You just have to look at Madonna, a not-so-brilliant singer, who's image and marketing have made her a global star.
In the Czech Republic, the services of a stylist are viewed with a certain amount of reservation.
Even celebrities often consider this to be money thrown away (the main thing is that I bring something, how I look is secondary).
And if any of us do get dressed, we should expect that he or she will likely force us to be a size smaller than he or she really needs.
And then you just have to Google it to be sure that the tabloids are saying that the celebrity has lost weight or gained weight again, and so on.
Jan and Mario urged us on Sunday not to believe that a stylist should focus on fashion and then "build" the outfit.
In his work, he must first communicate with the people he is styling and he must be a skilled psychologist.
Judging people without offering to be judged and having his own opinion.
"When some manager asks us to go through her closet and pick out some nice items, we can't just go through the whole closet and say, 'Oh, my God, that's terrible.'"
"You have to find at least a few commendable things to recommend what to wear", says Mario.
He also showed us in real terms what a so-called "plate bag" must contain.
A bag that you can put on your waist and carry all the necessary belongings.
In addition to such clear items as scissors, hair removal rollers, and safety pins, it includes such utensils as a nylon thread (which helps the stylist to photograph products such as handbags or hats), special clips to tighten the back of the garment if it is too large (needles or other clips are prohibited to prevent the fabric from breaking) and, of course, sewing.
So that we could not only listen but also try something practical, we learned how to properly tape shoes.
Even when you're shooting in a studio with a flat floor, you can damage the soles of your shoes, let alone the ones outside.
We were glued together and glued together...
The scissors must not be touched, lest they be damaged.
So you really have to be smart.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without limitation.
The skill I mentioned is not exactly my strong suit.
All of this was only a fraction of what we heard in the second weekend resumption class.
One thing I've learned is that professional styling is not a cakewalk.
V for Speed: The Run - the illegal race across America
The
The originally carefree ride is transformed by a series of completely avoidable, amateurish mistakes into a routine drive to the morning shift.
The ambitions were largely achieved, but what good was it if no one was willing to do a little more?
Even before it hit the shelves, the new installment, subtitled "The Run", was raising expectations.
He did promise to take the long-running Need for Speed series to a new level, and in the playable demo examples, he didn't seem to be just another one of many action racing games.
We were also curious to see what the most appropriate passages are missing, where the main character gets out of the car and walks on.
But as you're used to with NFS, the end result is a lot different than you'd expect.
Sure - they're potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is marred by some superfluous bugs that have been present in this series for a few years now, more or less.
So they're not really mistakes anymore, but rather signs of a laziness that is basically incomprehensible to game developers.
The adventure is starting very well.
First introduced to the story, the main character Jack has some personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the West Coast, you get behind the wheel and the task is to be the first to New York.
The basic idea has a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You never get the feeling that this game is offering the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very pretty, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing that's going to make a world of difference.
But the drive through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
From time to time, unusual elements bring a little variety to each race.
In the desert, for example, you're surprised by a desert storm that severely limits your view.
In the mountains, you have to be very careful not to get hit by an avalanche.
Besides, the races are all pretty well integrated.
A few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the clock), then a personal duel with a single opponent awaits you.
And then the police get involved, and they want to screw you over.
A novelty is the scene where Jack leaves the car.
It's more like some kind of interactive animation where Jack is running away from someone and the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, there are far fewer such passages in the play than you'd expect (specifically, probably only three).
In the end, this is more to the advantage of the thing, because this element at least has no chance of becoming boring - it is in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the preceding parts.
That is to say, from today's point of view, while it does not uproot trees, on the other hand, it could not be said to be bad.
If you're looking for realistic simulations, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But for an action-packed racing car, the local model will still do quite well, although better could be found in the competition.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems only appear after a certain time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK.
You wouldn't expect a game like this to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how the car is going to behave before it hits anything, then obviously it's not all right.
A typical example is when you are overtaking or passing oncoming cars, where you can only "hit" the other car in some places, but in other, almost identical situations, you can get into a fight and do wildly crazy things.
Or the car will be scrapped.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter, but it's annoying.
The restarts are solved this way: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then you throw the game back to the last clue point of the track.
- Only in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you've exhausted them, everything starts again.
So the restarts are more like a tool in case something doesn't work out, but you shouldn't rely on it.
But sometimes even the reboot doesn't help, because there's nothing else that helps but memorizing the critical section.
What's really unpleasant is that the same things happen in the same places all the time.
For example, some curves require you to pass in a very specific way, otherwise you simply will not pass.
Otherwise, you will always encounter "civilian" cars in the same configuration at the appropriate place, whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or one minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see the other car passing in front of you, playing with two cars, but by the time you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed to make this situation happen right in front of you.
The counterparts have other advantages.
There are a few times throughout the game where you're always overtaken by the same opponent in the same spot, and again, regardless of the time.
The craziest thing is that this is the end of the game on the long bridge, which you cross in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously overtake one of us here.
And then when it's in front of you, it takes your view, so you start driving your car around a few times.
- Of course you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so obvious that it quickly takes away the joy of the game.
And that's a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes so action-packed that you almost don't know where your head is.
And it doesn't matter what the "fault" is - the concept of fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in such a way that no boredom can arise, or something else entirely...
Another unusual idea is the change of car during the race.
Do not overlook the gas stations along the route, where you can change cars, although in most cases the car you have now will suffice.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limos for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical trips, for example on the mountain serpentines.
Hand in hand with the story mode is the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual localities that you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points to be gained for one's own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the story.
To get to the higher driver level, various objects must be opened: starting from the car, to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also linked to the online function Autolog, which compares the own results with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
One of the more incomprehensible carving is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you can drive to a subway tunnel (meinetwegen), where you can ride along the tracks in the dark (meinetwegen).
The speed gauge is between 100 and 200 km/h (for me), but then suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you uncompromisingly to the scrap.
I think we're gonna have a long debate in our editorial office about whether this was a blackout by the game developers or whether the authors think we're that stupid.
The technical side is not overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
What's more annoying is that at some moments of excitement, the refresh rate slows down, sometimes quite dramatically.
This is particularly the case in accidents involving a large number of persons, where continuous FPS is of no use.
The soundtrack is fine, and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a younger audience, a soundtrack was created "with something for everyone" - but who buys such a game just for the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run?
If the game weren't diminished by the totally unnecessary errors I mentioned, we could have claimed with the breast of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But it kind of makes the game seem unfinished.
A great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared to be blindfolded by the power of airport traffic lights.
Concert by the Students of the Velvet Revolution with the Charles University Choir
The Festa Academica Festival is now for the third time offering a musical experience that links World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution.
During the festival, the twenty specialist and university choirs will introduce themselves.
The festival will focus on the two concerts on November 17.
Charles University has a big stake in the festival.
"The participants include the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, and the festival committee includes the rector, Václav Hampl", said the head of the organising team, Jakub Čaloun.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of vocational schools choirs, which will take place on November 17 from 2 pm on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the important Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening, the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place in the halls of the People's House in Vinohrady, with the participation of university choirs, including choirs from Charles University.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music at the highest level to the public and to promote creative cooperation between young people.
The main organiser is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The event was sponsored by Bohuslav Svoboda, the Lord Mayor of the capital city of Prague, and Václav Hampl, the rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place in Prague and Pardubice from 16 to 20 November.
The schedule includes not only festival concerts but also numerous music meetings, student happanings, matinees and other events.
The festival is organised by the Ministry of Culture and the Ministry of Culture.
