The innovator IBM enters its second century of existence
If you were to look for a word that best describes IBM's strategy, it would be "longitudinalism".
To the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, and is known as a modern company, even though it was founded a century ago.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by its first chief - the visionary Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He was the man who said that countless problems in the world could be solved if people would just think a little.
His slogan "Think!" became the trademark around which the future giant's life was to be played (and at the same time the title of the internal magazine, which IBM began publishing in 1935).
This was also the basis of the company culture that Watsen had carefully prepared.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a century because it stuck to its principles and didn't shrink from changing everything around it.
And that allowed us, over the course of our first century, to transform technology, business, and society.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director, in a statement to mark the anniversary.
A well-thought-out system
