Changes in rice prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorised state-run travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies then mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, and only selected people were allowed to travel to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea, and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern bloc (including Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If a citizen of the C.S.S.R. wanted to travel to Poland or even the Soviet Union, for example, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or spend the night in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
It was not that way, either.
The so-called foreign currency - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, and without a currency peg it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the interior, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend homes and Danes - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, which is no longer recognised today, is that until 1989 it was impossible to travel to Croatia, the most popular holiday destination of the Czechs, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 1990s, the requirement to exchange currency was abolished in neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time, the Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their trips to the West, and everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers, for example, slept in a tent in the park when travelling to Paris, since who could afford to stay in a hotel or a guesthouse at that time?
A typical feature of Czech trips abroad was a trunk full of canned goods, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech koruna - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, average wages rose, and 1997 was another important year.
The increase in demand for travel has led to the fact that after 1997 travel agencies began to arrange regular travel by charter flights, which, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts, made air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already had currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-samet travel came in 2000 when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand - was made.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have been taking off to distant sunny lands every year, and this year, 12 exotic destinations are being flown directly from the Czech Republic.
Every year, about 100 000 Czechs travel to exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely put our country among the highly developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czech people spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 000 per head for a single holiday including the cost of the holiday destination.
