By Julia Stanek
The European Union is a major player in the world's transport and communications industry, and it is the world's largest supplier of transport and communications equipment.
A book that shows you where the best places to go are in the water.
When Iris Meder went on research trips in the past year and a half, one thing was always in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying on her back, she gazed up at the intricately designed domes, swam toward the marble pools that awaited her at the edge of the pool, and marveled over meticulously restored youth-style swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she would quickly record it in her notebook - including interesting details about the building's construction and history.
More than 200 swimming pools were explored by architectural historian Meder in this way - and she presents them in her recently published book "Badgefreuden": Volksschwimmälen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
She visited 13 countries on her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true enthusiast of bathing culture.
Meder says that she has no problem with sports - only water.
The only annoyance is that swimming fans have to put up with blue tiles and chlorine tanks, while joggers can breathe in the enchanting scent of spruce forests or listen to the joyful chirping of birds in the park.
"One day I asked myself why swimming pools have to be so ugly", says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths".
Water surface doubled architecture
The wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have put effort into it, swimming pools can be a real treat: "In bathrooms, instead of a floor, you have a water surface".
"It is transparent on the one hand, but it also reflects the beauty of the whole building".
Everything is doubled visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, diving boards.
The small-format picture book "Badfreuden" (Bad Pleasures) contains 190 pages of information on the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all it makes you want to dive into the blue.
Meder, a pool collector, discovered some remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent healing baths, such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-rich reservoir in an ancient karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath with basins filled with alkaline water, located in a flask-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many outdoor heated pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: while the Dachbad in Zurich has the whole city in view, the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton has a view of the snow-covered Arlberg - and: in the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, steam rises from three open shells, while the mountains of the Ötztal valley rise to the sky in the background.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not every pool has the pool collector's meter for the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, and the Árpád Bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells so strongly of heating oil that you would hardly believe that you have landed in a health spa.
The smell comes from the almost black alkaline hydrocarbonated healing water, the slime of which sticks to your skin as you slide into the pool - a unique wellness experience.
However, Iris Meder was disappointed in one place in her search for beautiful bathing sites: when she wanted to visit the open air and sunbathing in the Czech town of Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a closed area.
The 1902 bath designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic has since been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
But the decline has been countered by a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
The bath has been built in three phases, and not only are there Romanesque elements from the time of its construction in 1844, but there is also a Moorish Alhambra-style hall that was added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite swimming pool of pool expert Iris Meder - and not just because it originates from the Black Forest.
"It is an achievement to combine so many different styles of construction into one great unity", says Meder.
With a palace like this, the thermal pool is obviously a side issue.
