21st House in Vienna
The Changed Pavilion
It 's written by Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural story with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian pavilion at the 1958 Brussels World Fair won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and decayed.
Now it's being reopened as a museum.
If modern postwar architecture is full of clear forms, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair is a striking and famous example.
Schwäzers Pavillon was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next World Exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus gun-shaped annex in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
After the World Exhibition, his pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna Southern Railway Station, rebuilt and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century was opened in it - the "20th House" was called it.
But the building was not suitable as a museum, not in terms of space and technology - no walls to hang art, no good climate.
But it was used until contemporary art in Vienna found a new home.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and falling more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday night, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens its first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every way.
The new beginning was made by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Galerie Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a doctorate in art history with a considerable career in her youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Salzburg, pushed the rebuilding with politicians and monumentalists, she obtained public funds and private sponsors and fixed the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the execution, Krischanitz was the ideal cast.
Not only because he had sensibly rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he had studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology and the pavilion was a "monstrously important place" for him, where he had viewed the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness in its relocation to Vienna and its reuse.
The current conversion had far more serious problems: the building was "a waste of energy", says Krischanitz.
The glass facade window profiles were replaced, fibreglass insulation was installed and the glass roof was replaced with special safety glass.
Cold-bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements made room for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides for the lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors are still there, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust-proof colour.
And the movie theater is still exactly the same as it was.
And all under the strict supervision of the Monument Authority and on a small budget.
"Often, a material had to be found that was good and cheap and that the Monument Protection Agency liked", says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the stresses, problems, and alterations, the building has remained flexible and light.
The European Parliament has been asked to vote on the report by the Committee on the Environment, Public Health and Consumer Protection.
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and yet it wants to "awaken the right consciousness".
In this case, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because an urban development has happened: around the Swiss Garden the completely newly planned "Mainbahnhofsquartier" is being built, with office and residential buildings.
And another stroke of luck may occur: the 21st house could be reinforced by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and it is heard that she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss Garden.
