"We found that it was not difficult to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's cover-up of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply have to use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just like marketers have done for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with Adds, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, they invited the Adds users to a survey that asked about their education, their attitudes toward violence, and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without ever leaving their offices.
"It's a fairly new research method", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not surprising. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
In a surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens".
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends like likes, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has seen the number of scientific papers with this page's name in the title rise by nearly 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people that you wouldn't normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"In the past, when you tried to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have allowed them in", says Bartlett.
"Facebook doesn't do that - you go directly to them".
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their binge drinking on Facebook were significantly more likely to have a drinking problem than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it", Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
"We found a way to identify at-risk children who otherwise would not have been found".
Facebook also constantly taps into the data of its own population.
The site's data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to - masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its vast trove of data available to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want to or not, and to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to give out your personal information.
But what if Facebook users were to become part of a survey they didn't even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online anything goes.
"I don't think many users have even considered the fact that a researcher could study their profile", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she was concerned, it was just her and her friends".
