7 lessons from the late Steve Jobs interview that was shown in a theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, singling out the tech genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted this week before special screenings in major markets, is how much this creative mind understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who was eager to make charts - a man who believed that many CEOs suffered from "a disease of thought", "that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there's a tremendous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely created the TV series "Triumph of the Idiots" about the rise of the personal computer, and he sat down with Jobs for over an hour, in one of the rare, in-depth conversations they've ever had.
By this time, it had been 10 years since Jobs had been forced out of Apple, and he was already hard at work on his new computer company, NeXT, and looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in specialist reports, he says the transcript of the interview was missing on delivery.
It wasn't until after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which is coming to the Landmark theater this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here appears surprisingly eager to explain his philosophies on technology and business strategy.
And incredibly thoughtful.
There are four times during the interview that there are longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, during which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism is revealed, when he seems impatient with Cringely's questions, prompting him to move more quickly on issues or side-effects of greater importance.
Recorded before the age of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, The Lost Interview seems somewhat uncanny, as Jobs evaluates what he thinks other companies are doing right or wrong and sets out his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous applause of Jobs' career, but to see Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the leap to greatness is something else entirely, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could be and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this, he went and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, "Why do you do things?" and the answer you always get is, "Oh, that's how it's done".
No one knows why they do what they do, no one in business really thinks about things.
I've seen that.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline Apple's accounting.
Bewildered by the way in which costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs" which were estimated on the basis of mere assumptions and then adjusted by "deviation" - he developed an automated factory which ensured that business costs could be determined to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was mocked:
Jobs talks about the Blue Box he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed you to sneak into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs' enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is infectious.
He describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while trawling through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent stuff around the world half a dozen times, and if you honked on the phone, it would come out a minute later on the phone next door", Jobs says, giggling.
"We were young and we learned that we could build something ourselves that could control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We both didn't know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, and that was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have existed without it.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank that Wozniak and he nearly pulled off when they called the Vatican via Blue Box in the middle of the night and wanted to speak to the Pope, while imitating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself answered the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At age 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs was offered a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views of what a company was and how well it treated its employees".
Later, Jobs was one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a small screen with a Braunschweig tube and I fell in love with it.
I would climb to the top of HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for them.
How to improve innovation:
In the interview, Jobs talks about how to invent new products spontaneously.
Early in his career, when he was building some circuit boards, he was asked by a client to put together the whole computer.
He worked on a 30-day payback schedule and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had with developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some pretty strong arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer".
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for $15 and that was incredibly believable.
The Commission has already taken a number of measures to ensure that the
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industry giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copier or printer, what?"
They have a monopoly on the stock, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it's] these people who ultimately run the companies and the product that push people out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is being eradicated by people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
It happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger, could have been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
They've got the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop that great idea, it changes and grows".
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
You have to make tunings, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5,000 of these things, these concepts, and then you put them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to sort of take the best stuff that humans have created and then trying to bring those things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We're always shameless about stealing great ideas.
Part of what made the Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for the computer industry, they would be doing fantastic things in other areas.
