How to Unmask a Lie
A glance at the headlines today shows how pervasive and widespread deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy dealing with sexual harassment allegations by several women, with both sides accusing each other of lying.
Penn State's administration is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was heard over an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself by circulating denials that were quickly refuted by compelling evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is being accused of campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it will forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton created when he lied during his second term in the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating at school and on college exams are common.
There have been instances of teachers giving students the answers to the examination questions, so that they themselves could do well on their examinations.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite send a message that lying and cheating is okay.
How much deception are we experiencing?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies are considered to be lies of convenience.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Learning to detect lies is important for everyone, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game like charades, where the goal is to yell "Ha ha!" the disguise of deception is a serious field of study based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities conducting far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stammer, blush and struggle.
This does not mean, however, that such liars are difficult to detect and expose.
A trained lie detector can penetrate the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, the subtle facial expressions, the questioning and the timing.
I've spent several years researching the scientific evidence in the vast and ever-growing field of deception, and it's clear that deception is a modern skill that's easy to learn and helps us navigate our way through our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or administering is part of your professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at assessing other people, engaging their interest, controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more often than women, and that men lie more often to protect the feelings of others, and that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as a wrongdoer, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know when someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the quality of the voice of your subject.
They should know better when someone is usually tripping their foot all the time, so they don't falsely accuse them of tripping their foot during a meeting.
Then watch for accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behavior.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that are ringing, not evidence of a cover-up.
People who cheat may freeze when they try to remember their story, perhaps pointing their feet toward the door or leaning toward the exit, changing their position in significant ways, or showing "post-employment relaxation", that deep, relaxing exhalation and change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often falsely signal that a job interview is over, just to look for this relaxation after the job interview.
Also, watch your subject's language.
Scott Peterson's outsider is famous for using the past tense when he claimed his murdered wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceivers may also use distant language, such as "I did not have sexual relations with this woman, Miss Lewinsky", or by repeating a tricky question in its entirety.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... to the best of my knowledge... to the best of my knowledge and conscience".
This makes the answer more perceptual than factual, often raising alarm bells.
There is no magic bullet to disguise lies, but you can learn skills that make disguising them possible.
Thanks to these skills, everyone is less likely to be a victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
