2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa as the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of the change and who had high hopes for economic growth, but due to the climatic adversities, growth was not possible, and the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of dollars in losses in agriculture, but also limited the growth of the national economy, causing a general decline in economic activity of 3.6% in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16%, which had a braking effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report on the effects of the frost published by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development (Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable), 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were partially destroyed, mainly in the vegetable, corn and chickpea crops.
The decline in economic activity until November has caused unemployment to rise continuously in the Mexican state.The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March 55 053 residents of Sinaloa were without employment, which is 4.53 percent of the working population.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors: Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), comments that the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing now is an increase in unemployment that is related to several factors, including liquidity losses in the marketplace as a result of the cuts in the money laundering legislation passed by Congress, because it is not easy for those who are prohibited from accumulating dollars to make them work for themselves, to invest them or to use them for something else", he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country to look for work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, partly because of the immigration problems and partly because it is difficult to find work there too, and these people stay and look for work here, which is causing unemployment to rise", he says.
Black-collar work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more difficult when one considers the high proportion of undeclared work, which according to INEGI comprises 60.38 per cent of the country's employees who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are accompanied by low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Governmental Agency for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5352 pesos as of September, much less than the national average of 7375 pesos.
Decline in the ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 will see the largest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last decade, with the Secretaría de Economía (the national economic authority) reporting that the FDI from January to June was $630,597, a decline of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Economic Development Agency) for its part, records a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mostly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In July, in the face of the economic crisis, the regional government applied to the National Congress for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to revitalise the economy.
Reactions
The first year of the government of Mario López Valdés made the inability of the government obvious to the representatives of the business community.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (National Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), said that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa has been really very poor this year. It's going to take a lot of work to regain the ground lost this year and in 2012 we have to double down. The efforts of everyone and especially the progress of the already well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated", he explained.
Slow economic growth
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the freeze. One of the most important effects is a slowing economy that is not moving enough to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will end the year far below our expectations", he said.
Redefining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Employers' Federation) in Sinaloa, said that the state must be encouraged to become more dynamic in productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done, and we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa", he said.
There's a lot to do
The Coparmex chairman stressed the importance of developing a vision for the future that would steer government efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress in government.
"There are areas where the government has done more, but what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work to do", he said.
