Court approves digital TV switch in Mexico for 2015
The switch from analogue to digital signals is one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of Mexico (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional actions brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, and by which the switch from analogue to digital signals must be postponed from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes necessary to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued the decree-law detailing the switch to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate, as it did not obtain the necessary qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality.
The draft lawsuit, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the radio and television regulations are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission of Telecommunications in Mexico), and therefore the decree would be contrary to the hierarchical principles and the reservation of law.
The only people who voted in favour of the project were Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the decree-law. After accepting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer appealed the decree-law and stopped all activities to establish digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Minister President expressed his disagreement with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Land government cannot regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration with general regulations.
"I also do not believe that doing so would undermine the independence of the regulator", she said, recalling that the central government is constitutionally responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, as it is the one that manages state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, and it leads to a better use of the radio spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The delay in the transition, she said, was a delay in taking advantage of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest, not just technical, "because it includes economic, social, political and security aspects".
These matters, she stressed, "require action by the whole system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction by the state, they contain a set of features that put the constitution in the hands of the central state government".
She recalled that many countries worldwide had already implemented the digital transition through the government, despite having highly specialised institutions.
"We cannot conclude that the government, by issuing the contested legislative decree, is interfering with the powers of the Congress, because the laws passed by the legislature are being respected", she said.
The possibility of counting ballots in Michoacán is being considered
According to PREP figures, the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still to be counted.
The possibility of single-counting is a reality in this year's elections in Michoacán, because according to the data released by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still to be counted.
In this context, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9 the electoral office had adopted a series of regulations to harmonize local regulations with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had neither adapted its political constitution, its electoral law nor its law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force at this election round.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional lawsuit filed by the local legislature, judging the vote of the state delegate on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", since the latter had no right to "decide on it or veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of counting the votes individually that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, it was now possible for the local electoral authority to count the ballots partially or fully.
The results in the minutes do not match; the minutes of the vote counting and calculation are not in existence or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of ballots that have been filled in may be counted if there is a difference of one percent or less between the presumed winner and the runner-up, provided that there is an express request at the beginning of the sitting from the party or coalition chairman who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The vote may also be counted in its entirety if, after the completion of the ordinary count, it is found that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has been second.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where according to PREP the difference between the first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
His last will and testament
His ashes will be scattered over the Zapaliname mountains, the family confirmed.
The remains of pilot Felipe Bacio Cortés were found on Sunday evening in Saltillo, his birthplace, where a funeral procession and a mass were held on Monday.
According to family members, the last will of the Lieutenant Colonel was that his ashes be scattered over the Zapaliname Mountains.
After a tribute, the family of Bacio Cortés returned to the capital of Coahuila, along with the other victims of the Mexican Air Force plane crash, and the closest people to the colonel attended the ceremony in Campo Marte.
At noon, the ashes of the Lieutenant Colonel landed on the funeral home, which is located on the Boulevard Nazario Ortiz Garza, and where the family members and friends came.
At 5:30 p.m., his remains were examined at the Saltillo Institute of Technology, prompted by his former high school technical high school classmates and his American football team, which Felipe Bacio had joined during his preparation for high school.
"He wanted to return to Saltillo and have his ashes scattered over the Zapaliname mountains, as he had always told his family and friends", said Sandra Bacio Cortés, the pilot's sister.
In her view, the lieutenant colonel had fulfilled all his dreams and she believes that he was living life to the full. "He was a successful man, exceptional as a father and a son, a loving brother and he always stood up for his family".
Felipe Bacio Cortés left the town of Saltillo at a very young age to enter the Air Force School of Zapopán, Jalisco.
Some people couldn't believe it, because they thought he would be dizzy even on a truck.
His nephew, Jorge Alberto Dávila Bacio, remembers him as a good man: "He had hardly arrived in Saltillo, and already the whole family wanted to welcome him, as on the occasion when he brought Martha Sahagún to Saltillo".
The young man recalls that even at the age of seven, he had driven to Zapopan for his family's graduation, so he knows that his uncle died while doing what he loved best: flying a plane.
A final farewell
The Mexican Air Force Lieutenant Colonel Felipe Bacio Cortés, was honored by the people and government, the Mexican Army of the Sixth Military District, the Mexican Air Force, the school principal and students of the Technological Educational Institute of Saltillo, where he studied in 1985 and excelled both in studies and sports.
Bacio Cortés died a few days ago when the helicopter he was flying crashed, along with the Secretary of State, José Francisco Blake Mora, and six other people from the same office.
At 18.05 the cremated remains of Bacio Cortés, citizen of Saltillo, arrived to be handed over by the funeral home to members of the Mexican Air Force, led by Major Jaime Martinez, in the forecourt of the barracks, where his family members were already waiting for him, including his daughter Amanda and his wife Cristina, his mother, siblings and other relatives, students and teachers.
