The new Italian government is to be formed on Wednesday
The newly appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the Italian President to introduce him to the new government that is to face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government which will face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president of the state, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present the President with the results of the talks with the political parties on the formation of a government.
"I want to reiterate my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to cope with these difficult times", the former EU Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The frame is well set", he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal, while Italy is struggling with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a hard-line austerity package demanded by European politicians to restore the shattered confidence in Italy.
The pressure to act quickly on Monti was further heightened by the volatile market situation which resulted in Italian government bonds being charged at 7% for 10 years, the same rate at which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for European bailouts.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian Confindustria industry association, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government with all our strength".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
The chances of success for Montis were greatly increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to bring good results", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential, because many of its members have so far spoken out against a government made up of a majority of technocrats, which Monti is forming.
Support from Parliament
The new government of Monti needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to his efforts or the delay in reforms could again cause a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also putting pressure on the Commission by stating that a failure by Montis would be a disaster.
Mr Monti began his debate on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' associations, as well as youth and women's organisations.
The session is to be closed on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has set in motion an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week when it was announced that Berlusconi would step down, the uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister has caused the cost of Italian government bonds to reach critical levels again.
A bailout of Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government must last until the next elections, expected in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms instead of pushing elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should be made up of only technicians, a sign of their concerns in the face of the process imposed by the pressure of the financial markets.
Political sources indicate that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the inclusion of people from the political sphere.
