"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam's bassist Jeff Ament says the band is ready to play one of their best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
More than 20 years have been waiting for them, but the band assures that for them, playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This was confirmed by the bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva last week from Brazil.
The band is on the South American leg of their tour celebrating their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they'll make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You are reading an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, playing Pearl Jam in Costa Rica is a dream come true: Do you realize what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is coming true for us too.
This is only the second time we've played in South and Central America, and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for a vacation. It's such a beautiful country that we'll probably stay there for a few more days.
It's exciting for us to get our music out there.
I'm asking you because the fans are so devoted to the band, they're experiencing the days leading up to the concert in the most intense way.
What do you say to your most ardent fans?
Thank you for being there for us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and we thank you for the wait, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert is going to be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put a little pressure on you from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we've put on in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've played some big shows in Sao Paulo and we're hoping that they've got us ready for this gig in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing, and we love the jungle, and that's why Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
A lot of our friends are surfers, and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends used to go to Costa Rica and Nicaragua to surf, and together with Mexico, they're great places to surf, and that's how we learned about it through people who love to surf.
With the tour coming up, you've put on some big shows with a lot of songs.
What are your plans for the Costa Rica event?
We've never played there, so we don't limit ourselves.
We're going to try to put on the best show possible with a lot of different songs, and we're going to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes a different song, so it's not easy to decide which one we're going to play.
Adding two or three songs to our repertoire that we have not played for a long time helps us to maintain our concentration and to surprise us by reminding us of the reasons why we liked those songs, otherwise they might be forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and I think it makes it more interesting for the audience.
This tour is to celebrate your 20 years of history.
Do you find it hard to believe in your success when you look back?
Yes, I totally did.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, and that sounds like a dream.
We're going to continue to build on that blessing and we're going to continue to love the fact that we're still making music together.
We love and are excited about making music.
We're lucky to be able to go to the places in the world that we've always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean to you to have actively participated in the birth of the Grunge?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We're good friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising and very unusual for a movement to emerge from a group of friends.
Every now and then, a band comes out of one city, but it's not unusual for five or ten groups to come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be a part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on tour and we're glad to still be friends with all of them and we're honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It's also very unusual for a band like yours to have stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been playing together for 21 years, and Matt joined us 13 years ago, which is a lot longer than most bands last.
First of all, I think we're all lucky to be alive and we care about each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, which gives each individual the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other and each other's music, and we couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame hasn't always been easy, but on the other hand, you've always been able to do whatever you wanted to do because of your success.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown up has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure we don't tour too much, because it's too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it brought into being, not obsess about being a famous rock star, which we never cared about anyway.
What are your memories of your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs, and at first it was great.
We were a band for three years, and until Andy (Andrew Woods) died, we had never released a record.
We were disappointed that it took us so long, and we're still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started the band with us, and when I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, and it was always a joy to go to work and laugh together and talk about music and football and many other things.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas are responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, Eddie Vedder in particular, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yeah, the production team sent us videos of several bands and we liked this band the best so we're curious to see what Las Robertas can do live, which will be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you're playing live?
That's a question for Ed, I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
Of so many
Some of the first people that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
