Fujimori was taken to the hospital for further medical examinations .
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss in his legs, his family doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights abuses during his 1990-2000 rule, has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which he has had four surgeries and is under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, his personal physician, told the television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas hospital in Peru to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that he believes Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not want to do so because he believes Fujimori is innocent.
He has had four operations for cancer of the tongue, and he has lost 40 pounds (18 kg), as well as other conditions, such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Fujimori has been held in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía prison since September 2007 and has been detained in the prison since then.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the Peruvian army's death squad, which operated clandestinely during his rule.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, consisting of several ministers and businessmen, will start its visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss regional policy issues.
Mujica will meet his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday, which, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the highlight of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón's support in the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries which still appeared as tax havens.
Mexico has held the presidency of the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries, and since January this year it has had an agreement with the South American country on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to speed up the implementation of tax information exchange agreements in order to be removed from the OECD's "grey list" of countries that have not adopted all international standards for tax cooperation.
At the commercial level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has existed since 2004, which has contributed to an increasing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The mustachioed installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the love of the girl in stereo technology.
The game, which is coming to store counters around the world this month, was designed from the outset to match the features of the Nintende 3DS handheld console, which can be played in three dimensions without special glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to tell how the stereoscope works without glasses", assured Omar Álvarez, the person responsible for Nintendo's press in Spain, at the launch of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game from Nintendo that was designed from the ground up for this console", because until now, success stories like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman emphasized that although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows for fast, fluid play.
Álvarez confirmed that Super Mario 3D Land contained two games in one: The first part is "easy" to capture the less-skilled users.
After that, the experts can "turn round" on the different levels of the game, which become increasingly difficult.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the bottom of the action.
Super Mario's journey into the three-dimensional world also marks the character's return to a portable console, something that has not happened since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo is winking at the fans of the saga and repeating the recipe of success of the last issues: the moustached installer must overcome dangerous platforms to free Princess Peach.
