Colom guarantees Portillos' extradition to the United States
The President of Guatemala, Álvaro Colom, announced this Tuesday that he would extradite former Governor Alfonso Portillo to the United States to face charges for conspiring to launder $70 million.
The process of the US requesting Portillo's extradition to face trial in the US is over.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the government, considering that a decision-making court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that during his administration he had not interfered with court decisions and had granted all extradition requests that had come to his attention.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is being extradited for murder and aggravated assault, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
The Colom procedure is a government act that takes place when all judicial and constitutional instances for the conviction of the former president of the state (2000-2004) have been exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala is clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of embezzling 120 million quetzales from the Ministry of Defense during his government, a trial that preceded the extradition, but the Minister countered and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people facing social exclusion
The organisation was set up to prevent the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of Trinijove's existence have brought important results: in this quarter of a century, 6000 young people threatened with social exclusion have been helped to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, over 100 jobs have been created for this social group.
The anniversary was marked yesterday by an event attended by over 300 people at the former factory of Fabra i Coats.
Trinijove was set up in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems, who were at risk of marginalization.
