Park or mountain?
The architects have agreed to the tender, apart from the disputes over the fees.
The 16 Gates urban tender reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the latter published its libel against the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It has even been compared in numbers to New York's Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park was seen by many as the upper limit of Barcelona, as the Catalan capital is one of the few that does not extend north-south, but up (mountain) and down (sea).
The classification of Collserolas as a natural park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone, with the boars in the role of the Yogic bear.
This was achieved when the city issued a huge tender in September, comprising 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
No doubt a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that, or someone's planning to put gates on the land.
The question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for tenders is the topic of discussion among all Barcelona architects, not only from an organisational point of view but also in terms of reflection on the city.
It's almost a recurring theme that two members of this long-established caste, who meet in the elevator, can fall back on.
And this very fact provides the material for one of the rare coincidences between what three architects from Barcelona think about it and some university professors who applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán, it is "necessary" to speak of the "Front at the Mountain" after the attack on the coast, insofar as the speech of Ildefons Cerda, who spoke about the green apples, has not been delivered.
"We should assume that the beach is Barcelona's biggest park.
One of the reasons is that he is very accessible.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect, for whom the title "Collserola Gate" contains a "lexical trap": it must not be "conceived as access to a park, but as a limitation of areas where it is necessary to trade".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona, who have experience in urban planning, considers the proposal an "intellectual challenge" which "contains some dangers".
The European Council of Ministers for Education and Culture has adopted a resolution on the future of the European Schools, which calls for the development of a European school of education and training.
The first fear is the limitation of what can be built.
"To limit something always means to define the next step", i.e. to go beyond it.
"We need to think about new urban planning tools, because the current ones [the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM) ] can lead to a real disaster".
Modol, who is more closely concerned with the question, says that, in a simplified way, the side of Collserola which goes towards Vallesana "can be understood as a park which does not go towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola which should not be "leaked out", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving his body the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
He also notes that the mountain's proximity to the city is the cover letter that allows architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams created ("just the right one", he says). "We architects should only be a tool".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex because the conditions of the tender do not give a global view of Collserola: "16 competitions were announced in the cross-section", he says, "on the mountain-sea axis, but there is no longitudinal perspective that considers the area as a whole".
In his case, at least, that's what got him into the 16 contests.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next door.
In his opinion, the city should ensure that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped throughout its length in such a way that a soft transition between the city and green zones is created.
