Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven others.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat of Communications and Transportation in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation into the accident, in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people were killed, indicate that the helicopter, with its entire structure intact, crashed directly into the ground, without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing made contact with trees at 25 metres altitude, with the helicopter losing its fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had several ground contacts".
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers, so it met all the requirements for transporting the personnel.
He also said that the search of the area where the plane had landed did not find any helicopter parts.
"The search did not find any aircraft parts in other places, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, so it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
The priority at present is to get the results as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), said that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial was flying at cruise speed when it hit the ground and that the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the belief that at the time of impact, this was a normal flight operation".
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, identified six relevant points to be taken into account in the inquiry:
Flight of the aircraft:
In accordance with the rules of the airline, this was a flight under the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew would have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded favorable weather conditions on takeoff, and during the flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico, some low-hanging clouds were lifted.
Routes selected
It's possible that the crew chose a lower area with better visibility toward the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Point of impact:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter are in agreement, but it is possible that there was no loss of control or deviation from the flight path before the impact.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a restricted area:
The information available so far indicates that the helicopter was hit from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered debris suggests that the helicopter, with its structure intact, was struck by the ground.
No signs of fire or explosion:
The remains of the plane at the scene of the accident do not suggest fire or explosion.
The latest analysis indicates multiple contacts to the ground.
The site investigations found aircraft parts at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level, a terrain that is steep and has a gradient of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke down.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a thorough search of an area beyond the restricted area at the crash site, no scattered aircraft parts were found, reinforcing the belief that the intact structure of the aircraft was impacted against the ground.
MSS announces research protocol to find the gene for obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (IMSS) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, called "Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity", which aims to find the genetic markers associated with overweight.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Medical Research Unit, focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team was set up, consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The public is invited to participate in the study, and those interested can come to the IMSS sports fields in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out with children and young people every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation started at the sports ground of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and since October 8 it has been continued at the sports ground of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México).
If the target of 500-600 subjects is reached, the study will be continued in the sports ground of Independencia (south of the capital district) and completed in that of Morelos (north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On World Diabetes Day, he said that he would try to get 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 to fill out questionnaires about their diet with their parents' consent and under their supervision.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and their family history of illness to check for risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also explained that on the Saturdays mentioned, the subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure was checked and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors were determined (test to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this study was being carried out in response to the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in weight in young people.
"The health surveys conducted in 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys had increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls by 47 percent, and that obesity had also increased dramatically", stressed the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that on average, a Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In a very general way, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) that we take in, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants would be to have a comprehensive examination of the children to determine whether they were overweight or obese.
It would even look at the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and in the forearm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-diabetes.
All information would be kept confidential and the parents would be informed in writing by the doctors, who would explain all the test results to the parents and suggest lifestyle changes appropriate to prevent illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that contribute to overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: lack of physical activity, spending most of the day watching television, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamala, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, and the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from the UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the UNAM University of Mexico, develops polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs of the pavement were followed, it would not be necessary to repair the almost 200,000 impact holes that will be created when the rainy season begins in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (Mexico Valley Metropolitan Area), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the UNAM University, warning that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt pavement were done properly, the number of impact holes would be greatly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his talk "Blowholes from a Technical Point of View", given on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he runs is developing polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to asphalt but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight called asphaltene, and the other part has a low molecular weight called malthene, and together they give the road surface its characteristic elastic behavior.
The coelastis­tic behaviour of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of nearly 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the strength of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes from one day to the next depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations", explained the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City have a majority of a flexible pavement composed of six layers of material, the last three of which include asphalt.
Between the uppermost layers is a layer of asphalt, which is made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single pebble of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows for good force distribution in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed", said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer", he explained, "is a final layer, called the 'tread layer', which is made up of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
As these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and must produce friction.
The road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the tread layer also needs a suitable thickness and the material of which it is made must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water", he said, "as it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the ground becomes damp, water enters the layer and is difficult to get out again, causing all the layers of the road surface to soften and, as a result, to create potholes.
"When a hole is created", he said, "the first layer of the roof is removed, and the wear layer is only later affected, but the damage is not immediate, but a process that should be maintained at the first sign through appropriate maintenance programmes".
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that vehicle load is another important cause of potholes, so that the thickness of each layer of road surface must always be in proportion to vehicle load and that it must be ensured that this rule is respected to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and which allow the repair of potholes to be carried out easily and without the use of high temperatures.
