So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A scannerman from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4th, a Lophoscopist from the CTI (Cali Prosecutor's Office) was identified as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) - "Alfonso Cano" by comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscope operators in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working in criminal investigations for 21 years, was on call.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the communities of Chocó, where he often had to travel for five days in the jungle to reach the location of the bodies he was to identify.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialised in Lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is subject to friction, i.e. the hand and foot surfaces.
In the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was instructed to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
He flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca on Friday night.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of them might be that of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he had to take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived at the location of the body with the examiner, he could not identify him because his physical appearance was not at all similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints are not a lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting cell, and a flashlight, Eleazar compared the corpse's fingerprints with those on the printed page.
He had seen right, it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for informing the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
Searching for Traces
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of the "Cano" was very important.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
The science of dactyloscopy is an exact science with no margin of error, which can be a key factor in solving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also assist in homicide and robbery investigations and confirm the identity of arrested individuals.
When arrested, many criminals present false identification documents or do not have any.
We'll take their fingerprints and run them through the database.
The researcher told us that during a burglary, he had to tear a piece of wall from a house because the thief had put his hand on this very spot when he was taking out a safe that was stuffed with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the entire handprint and identify the criminal who had participated in several thefts", he recalled.
Fingerprints can also be used to exonerate or incriminate murder suspects.
A body was recently found surrounded by liquor bottles.
The investigation suspected that a family member might be a suspect, and indeed, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI fingerprint technician explained that "fingerprints are taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents".
If they appear, a plant cell or a conveyor belt is used.
After that, the prints are sent to ASIF, which is the criminal database, or to the registrar.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers", explained the CTI expert.
He said that not everything was as portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as all that glitters is not gold, all that you touch is not a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a proper comparison.
