Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and directly connects Western Europe with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is designed to supply gas to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glitz and glamour.
The European Parliament has been asked to take a decision on the future of the gas pipeline, which is to be opened in the near future.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically turned the wheel of the valve that feeds Russian gas into the West European network.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year through a first pipeline of 1,224 km, connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, to Western Europe.
A second pipeline, which will allow a total delivery of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of France's total consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the possibility of building a third line on the same route is already being mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous structure is a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will allow direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any transit through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little bit of their power: it is now more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close off access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the most active in the debate, did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the Hitler-Stalin alliance for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this came at the cost of weakening European energy, as the project has created a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has been able to achieve its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries, which have a high consumption of gas and whose gas reserves are running low, in just five years.
'This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us in an organic way,' François Fillon said at the inauguration of the pipeline, pointing out the political and economic importance of the major gas contracts.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom managers, who are very much represented in Lubmin, in regard to the pipeline.
The construction of this pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel with a concrete sheath to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, about 200 meters deep.
The construction of the bridge had to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"About a hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long metal snake, weighing 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything along its length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned for the Swedish coast, but the project managers have refused to do so because the Swedes were not interested in seeing a Russian state company permanently settling on their shores.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will close the gas passage in less than a minute", Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission line escapes into the air.
This is considered by the designers to be unlikely, as the weld seam was estimated to have a leakage resistance of one per 100,000 years.
The state surveillance of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled from a seagoing vessel for external observation purposes and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It is shaped like a cigar, about a metre in diameter, is inserted into the inside of the pipeline and is moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 metres per second, the device provides the most accurate information on arrival on any deformation of the metal.
The gas transmission line was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to make this project a reality.
However, the management of the company remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The German companies E.ON and BASF are also included (each 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (both 9%).
These five companies have formed a consortium called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the actual amount of gas transported is", said Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas transmission line was covered by 30% of the capital by the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For example, GDF Suez's investment was 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are determined to recover their costs, since Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-forested coastal strip near Lubmin.
The 15 feet (4.5 m) high valves form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is fed into the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour, and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand name notebook.
Created by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours added by candlelight with the writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular cover, its rubber band, its egg-white pages, as if aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a distinctive design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a technical adviser to the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old production technique called mole skin, which is a wooden lacquer used, for example, for upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has brought back to life an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and reached 12.7 million units.
This is a far cry from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook is of interest to businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of a cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded clientele.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now employs over 100 people and has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York, since 2008.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in city centres and is committed to asserting its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of the times and its new writing needs, which persist despite the rise of e-mail", explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural character is accompanied by the development of Moleskine: the brand recently launched an exhibition called "Detour (Umweg) " in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard-shaped cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and knew how to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand has the entire range of articles.
A success that sets Neider on the map: In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of the company Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of the disabled remain so high?
Approximately 19% of the disabled are looking for a job.
Today marks the beginning of the 15th Disabled Work Week.
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is consistently twice the average: 19% against 9% for the general population.
Discouraging you?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, director general of the Adapt association, which organises the 'Working Week for the Disabled'.
"The progress made in fifteen years is considerable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not double, but triple".
"Nevertheless, there is still a tremendous amount of work to be done".
However, it must be said that for the disabled unemployed, numerous obstacles remain before they can get a job.
The elderly are more likely to suffer from this problem: 37% are over 50 years old (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with a higher education.
Finally, longterm unemployment is also very widespread: 53% among the disabled compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the workforce, and these are "the core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes of mind which, although they are certain, are slowly evolving.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the magazine La Cité indicated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge about disabled people", which was "overrepresented" by "people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually handicapped".
The result is that private firms with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was set by a law of 1987.
These latter figures, which date from 2008, refer to a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director-general of Agefiph, the organisation responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence: the number of 'fees-paying' establishments and the total amount paid have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 (and from 606 to 480 million euro).
"The 2005 law providing for contributions increases put a lot of pressure on companies", said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises employ between 20 and 49 disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
"What a stroke of luck".
